DNCE’s “Cake by the ocean” is actually a euphemism for having an intimate interaction with someone on the beach. By virtue of this, the lyrics of this song are full of sensual innuendos. However, they are not that obvious. In fact “Cake by the Ocean” is often interpreted as a kids’ song, and it comes as a shock to some people when they discover what the lyrics are actually based on. 

Indeed for the most part, “Cake by the Ocean” reads like the average fare of a man trying to get with a lady he is interested in. And a child can easily decipher the singer’s intentions to truly be just to enjoy “eat(ing) cake by the ocean”. 

In fact Joe Jonas, the leader of DNCE has explained that the lyrics are open to interpretation by the listener, calling this track “a party anthem for any occasion”.  So if you enjoy being intimate with your partner on a beach or literally eating pastries on the seaside, this song is applicable. Also, considering that it uses “cake” as part of its imagery (including having a giant depiction of one on the music video), it is likely, as Joe suggested, that this track will remain a popular all-around party song despite its sensual foundation. 

Facts about Cake by the Ocean:

This was the first single DNCE ever dropped.

They dropped this tune on 18 September 2015, over a year before the album it was featured on, DNCE, was released on 18 November 2016. However, it was also included on their 2015 EP, SWAAY.
The label that published this song is Republic Records.

Mattman & Robin (Mattias Larsson and Robin Fredriksson) are also co-writers of this track along with DNCE lead singer Joe Jonas and American musician Justin Tranter.

“Cake by the Ocean” has been performed in family-friendly venues such as the 2016 Radio Disney Music Awards and the 2016 Kids’ Choice Awards. As such, there is a Clean Version of the song that is devoid of direct sensual references.

The clean version also makes an appearance in the video game Just Dance 2017.

This song is in the films Pitch Perfect 3, Bad Moms, Middle School: The Worst Years of My Life, Malibu Rescue and in trailers for Mike and Dave Need Wedding Dates and Hotel Transylvania 3: Summer Vacation.It has also been featured in the television series Telenovela, South Park, No Tomorrow, The Real O'Neals, The Challenge Dirty 30 and Mary + Jane, and appeared in an Indonesian Mizone commercial in August 2016.The clean version of the song is a playable track in Just Dance 2017. 

Cake by the Ocean” reached number-9 on the Hot 100. Furthermore, it reached number 7 in Canada and went on to become the second-most played song on the radio in Canada during 2016, preceded only by Justin Beiber’s “Love Yourself”.

“Cake by the Ocean” peaked at number one on the music charts in several countries, including Argentina, Israel, Japan and Mexico. 

This song has been certified quadruple-platinum in Italy, triple-platinum in Australia and the United States and double-platinum in Brazil. It was also certified double-platinum in Canada and the United Kingdom. In France, Germany as well as Sweden, it also went platinum. 

DNCE stands out with a quirky look and lyrics that are even quirkier, thanks in large part to their international team that didn't all grow up speaking English. It was their freewheeling songwriting style that resulted in this track. Jonas told Entertainment Weekly: "We were just creating stuff to create. 'Cake By The Ocean' could be free and wild, and we didn't stress too much about having it follow the rules of songwriting."


The line "I'll be Diddy, you'll be Naomi" is a reference to the model Naomi Campbell and the music mogul Sean Combs, who has gone by the names "P. Diddy" and "Diddy." Campbell and Combs dated in 2002 when he was going by P. Diddy.

The year after this song was released, the R&B singer Maxwell released a similarly titled track: "Lake By the Ocean."

So what happened to the missing "A" in DNCE? Speaking with New York radio station Z100 just before the song's premiere, Lee said its imperfectness is sort of a mission statement for the band, demonstrating that you don't have to be a pro dancer to show off your moves.

Guitarist and producer Nile Rodgers turned down the chance to produce this track. He told The Sun: "I was supposed to do that but I just wasn't available. Now I always make a joke and say, 'Don't worry dudes, I've got it next time.'"
